Fig. 2
a and b indicated that the increase in MgAC-CDs typically leads to a rise in photocatalytic performance of MgAC-CDs/TiO2, under both UV and visible light irradiation. The photocatalytic activity of MgAC-CDs/TiO2 samples under UV irradiation was higher than that of visible light irradiation (see Table 1
). Among all the MgAC-CDs/TiO2 samples, MgAC-CDs [0.20 g]/TiO2 had the highest photocatalytic performance under both UV light and visible light. For MgAC-CDs [0.30 g]/TiO2 sample, a slight decrease in its photocatalytic activities can be related to the coverage of active sites on TiO2 due to surface overloading or the formation of new defects/recombination centers [11,30]. Moreover, the overloading of MgAC-CDs/TiO2 led to a decrease in surface area (see Table S1). Compared to MgAC-CDs/TiO2 samples, TiO2 had limited photocatalytic activities under UV light and no photocatalytic activity under visible light. Thus, it could be concluded that the presence of MgAC-CDs can shift the photocatalytic activities of composites into the range of visible light. The photocatalytic performance of MgAC-CDs [0.20 g]/TiO2 is up to 3rd cycle with a similar MB removal rate (∼80%). Up to 5th cycle, the activity of MgAC-CDs [0.20 g]/TiO2 is slightly decreased, but still at acceptable levels (∼65%) (see Fig. S2). The reduction of photocatalytic performance could be related to the loss of TiO2 or the accumulation of MB intermediate products from the former cycle on active sites of nanocomposites [31].
